  <subsection xml:id="subsec-DAR-sliding-dilation">
    <title>A Dynamic Look at Dilations</title>
  <exploration xml:id="explore-sliding-scale">
    <title>Role of the Scale Factor</title>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Use <xref ref="fig-vary-scale-factor"/> to complete the tasks
                in this exploration. This GeoGebra applet allows us to see how changing 
                the scale factor affects the dilation.
            </p>
        </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
               With the slider for the scale factor set at <m>s=3</m>, 
               how is quadrilateral <m>A'B'C'D'</m> related to <m>ABCD</m>?
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-vary-scale-factor">
                <caption>
                    GeoGebra applet for <xref ref="explore-sliding-scale"/>
                </caption>
                <interactive xml:id="slide-scale-app"
                platform="geogebra">
                <slate surface="geogebra" material="qjarc5rc"/>
              </interactive>
            </figure>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                What happens when the scale factor <m>s=1</m>? Why?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                What happens when the slider is moved to <m>s=0</m>? Why do you
                think that happens?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                What happens when the slider is moved to a number between 0 and 
                1?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                What happens when the slider is moved to <m>s=-\frac{1}{2}</m> ?
                <m>s=-1</m> ? <m>s=-2</m> ? Describe the effect of a negative 
                scale factor on a dilation.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Construct the four lines, <m>\overleftrightarrow{EA}</m>,
                <m>\overleftrightarrow{EB}</m>, <m>\overleftrightarrow{EC}</m>,
                and <m>\overleftrightarrow{EA}</m>. What do you notice about 
                these lines and the image <m>A'B'C'D'</m> ? Is this true regardless 
                of the value of <m>s</m>?
            </p>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the reset tool (circle with arrows in upper right) to move the 
                slider back to <m>s=3</m> and delete the lines. Use GeoGebra tools 
                to measure the lengths <m>EA</m> and <m>EA'</m>,
                <m>EB</m> and <m>EB'</m>, <m>EC</m> and <m>EC'</m>, and 
                <m>ED</m> and <m>ED'</m>. What do you notice about these pairs of
                measurements? Experiment with moving center <m>E</m> or some 
                of the vertices of <m>ABCD</m>. Does your conjecture still hold?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <aside>
            <p>
                For smaller fonts, measure segments instead of the distance between 
                points. The <sq>Segment</sq> tool is provided.
            </p>
        </aside>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the reset tool again to move the 
                slider back to <m>s=3</m> and delete the measurements. Use the GeoGebra 
                tools to measure the four sides of the original quadrilateral, 
                <m>AB</m>, <m>BC</m>, <m>CD</m>, and <m>DA</m>. Compare these 
                to the measures of the four sides, <m>A'B'</m>, <m>B'C'</m>, 
                <m>C'D'</m> and <m>D'A'</m> of the dilated quadrilateral. 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
            <p>
                Some measurements may be approximated by rounding. This could 
                lead to small discrepancies in values.
            </p>
        </hint>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Measure the area of quadrilateral <m>ABCD</m> and its image 
                <m>A'B'C'D'</m>. Move the slider as helpful to determine how 
                the area of a figure is affected by the scale factor.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
            <p>
                The area of the image will be <m>s^2</m> times the area of the 
                original figure where <m>s</m> is the scale factor for the 
                dilation.
            </p>
        </answer>
    </task>
  </exploration>
